equation_narrative.headline: Glycine emerges from structural flexibility constraint at tight turn position
equation_narrative.story: Position 10 in ubiquitin sits in a tight turn between two beta strands, requiring exceptional backbone flexibility. Early layers (1-12) show a hydrophobic-leaning representation (alanine peaks at 34% at L12) as the model reads local sequence context rich in small hydrophobic residues (VKT-LT). The representation shifts dramatically at L16 when structural constraint features activate (F16:10 projects 0.617 toward G), recognizing this position's need for conformational freedom. By L21, glycine dominates at 79%, and decision-phase MLP neurons (L28-32) strongly reinforce this with G-specific features reaching 99.6% confidence.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-12 assemble a hydrophobic-leaning representation driven by local sequence context. The position is flanked by small residues (T8, T12) and lysines (K6, K11), creating an initial representation consistent with small hydrophobic amino acids—alanine peaks at 34% in the logit lens at L12. However, structural reading begins around L9-14 with attention heads scanning nearby positions. The critical shift occurs at L16 when feature F16:10 (0.617 projection) activates, encoding structural flexibility requirements. This feature strongly favors glycine and acidic residues (E, D also elevated), suggesting recognition of a conformationally constrained position. By L21, the representation has fully transitioned to glycine-dominant (79%), reflecting assembled evidence for a tight turn requiring backbone flexibility.
perception_phase.context_character: Tight turn position between secondary structure elements requiring exceptional backbone conformational freedom. Local sequence context is hydrophobic-leaning with small residues (T, L) but structural constraints override simple sequence patterns.
key_information_sources: Local sequence: flanked by threonines (T8, T12) and lysines (K6, K11), creating initial small-residue bias
Structural contacts: 2 contacts read by attention, indicating constrained local geometry
L16 structural constraint: F16:10 (attn, 0.617 proj) recognizes flexibility requirement, strongly favoring G/E/D
L21 MLP consolidation: N21:896 (0.556 proj), N21:4971 (0.465 proj), N21:1156 (0.450 proj) all vote strongly for glycine

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between L24-30 as glycine-specific MLP neurons activate with increasing strength. Layer 30 shows the strongest commitment with N30:272 projecting 1.231 toward glycine (also strongly favoring E/D, consistent with flexibility requirements). Layer 31-32 show transient suppression (negative MLP contributions from aromatic-favoring neurons like N31:3965), but layer 33 features F33:1155, F33:132, and F33:3601 (projections 144.6, 133.7, 133.6) deliver the final decisive vote, pushing confidence to 99.58%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from representation to decision. At L23, glycine reaches 88% in the logit lens—still a representation of structural constraint rather than a committed prediction. At L24, MLP neurons begin casting explicit votes: N24:4169 (0.513 proj) and N24:3797 (0.426 proj) activate as glycine-specific prediction channels. The representation transitions from 'this position requires flexibility' to 'this position is glycine.'

candidates.narrative: Glycine emerges decisively at L16 when structural constraint features activate (F16:10 projects 0.617), jumping from 5% to 22% in the logit lens. By L21, it reaches 79% as MLP neurons N21:896, N21:4971, and N21:1156 (projections 0.556, 0.465, 0.450) vote strongly for flexibility. The decision phase (L24-33) shows sustained commitment: L30 neuron N30:272 projects 1.231, and final-layer features F33:1155, F33:132, F33:3601 (projections 144.6, 133.7, 133.6) deliver overwhelming support, reaching 99.58% confidence.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L16, dominant by L21, final commitment L28-33
key_evidence: F16:10 (attn, 0.617 proj) — structural flexibility constraint recognition
N21:896 (0.556 proj) — glycine-specific writer, also favors W/E
N30:272 (1.231 proj) — strongest single neuron vote, favors G/E/D flexibility triad
F33:1155 (MLP, 144.6 proj) — final-layer glycine prediction channel

candidates.narrative: Alanine leads the logit lens from L5-13, peaking at 34% at L12. This reflects the representation's hydrophobic character during early perception as the model reads local sequence context rich in small hydrophobic residues (VKT-LT). However, this is not a prediction—it's an artifact of the representation correlating with small, hydrophobic amino acids before structural constraints are fully integrated. Alanine collapses after L16 when flexibility requirements dominate, falling to 1% by L23.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L5-13, peaks L12, collapses L16-23
key_evidence: L8-12: representation is hydrophobic-leaning, consistent with local sequence
Peak 34% at L12 reflects small-residue bias before structural reading completes
N12:3169 (-0.260 proj) and N12:1849 (-0.147 proj) erase alanine as flexibility constraint emerges

candidates.narrative: Serine shows 23% in the logit lens at L0 (embedding), reflecting its similarity to threonine in the local context (T8, T12 flank this position). This early prominence is purely representational—the embedding space groups small polar residues together. Serine briefly resurges at L14-17 (14% at L14) as polar features activate, but ultimately loses to glycine's structural flexibility advantage, falling to 0.05% by L33.
candidates.key_layers: High at L0 (23%), resurges L14-17, eliminated by L24
key_evidence: L0: 22.6% from embedding similarity to local threonines
L14-17: polar representation phase before structural constraint dominates
Suppressed by glycine-specific neurons in decision phase

candidates.narrative: Glutamate peaks at 7.4% at L11, appearing alongside aspartate (6.3%) as the representation briefly explores charged, flexible alternatives. Features like F16:10 that favor glycine also project toward E/D (0.534 and 0.377 respectively), suggesting the model recognizes this position could accommodate any highly flexible residue. However, glycine's unique lack of a side chain makes it the optimal solution for extreme conformational constraint, and E fades to 0.15% by L33.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L11, considered alongside D at L16, eliminated by L24
key_evidence: L11: 7.4% peak during flexibility exploration phase
F16:10 projects 0.534 to E (vs 0.617 to G) — flexibility recognition
N30:272 projects 1.719 to E (vs 1.231 to G) — E remains viable but G wins

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic-leaning (alanine at 19% L14) to flexibility-dominant (glycine at 22% L16) as structural constraint features activate. Feature F16:10 (attention, 0.617 projection) is the key driver, recognizing this position requires exceptional backbone freedom. Attention heads begin erasing hydrophobic candidates: L14 attention contributes -3.42 to velocity, actively suppressing the alanine-dominant representation. This is the moment the model transitions from encoding 'what's nearby' to encoding 'what structural role this position plays.'

Glycine surges from 28% to 88% as perception-phase MLP neurons consolidate the flexibility constraint. Layer 21 shows strong positive contribution (N21:896, N21:4971, N21:1156 project 0.556, 0.465, 0.450), while L22-23 show net negative MLP contributions (-0.17, -1.35 total) as the model suppresses remaining alternatives. This is the final perception-phase consolidation before the decision phase begins—the representation is now definitively 'flexibility-required' rather than merely 'small-residue-compatible.'

The final decision crystallizes through massive MLP neuron activation. Layer 30 contributes +4.88 total projection with N30:272 alone projecting 1.231 toward glycine. Layer 31 shows transient suppression (-4.31 total) as aromatic-favoring neurons like N31:3965 (-1.342 proj) fire, but layer 32-33 deliver the decisive commitment. N32:2263 projects 1.331, and final-layer SAE features F33:1155, F33:132, F33:3601 (144.6, 133.7, 133.6 projections) push confidence from 54% at L29 to 99.58% at L33. This is pure decision-making: glycine-specific prediction channels activating with overwhelming strength.

deep_dives.label: Early hydrophobic phase (L1-12)
deep_dives.caption: Examine features F1:5480, F1:9146, F9:5728 to see how the model initially encodes local sequence context. These features capture the hydrophobic character of nearby residues (VKT-LT), creating a representation that correlates with small hydrophobic amino acids like alanine. This is perception, not prediction—the model is reading what's here, not yet deciding what should be here.

deep_dives.label: Structural constraint recognition (L16)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 16 MLP is the turning point. Neuron N16:10 projects 0.617 toward glycine (and 0.534 toward E, 0.377 toward D), recognizing this position requires exceptional flexibility. Contrast with erasers N16:4756 (-0.449, favors E/Q/I) and N16:1647 (-0.261, favors N/T/Q) that suppress alternatives lacking flexibility. This is where structural constraint overrides sequence context.

deep_dives.label: Perception consolidation (L21-23)
deep_dives.caption: Watch glycine-specific writers activate: N21:896 (0.556), N21:4971 (0.465), N21:1156 (0.450) all vote for glycine. Layer 22-23 show net negative contributions as the model suppresses remaining alternatives (N22:893 erases L with -0.522, N23:869 erases T with -0.675). By L23, the representation is 88% glycine-consistent—the perception phase is complete.

deep_dives.label: Decision phase MLP (L28-32)
deep_dives.caption: The decision crystallizes here. L30 shows massive commitment: N30:272 projects 1.231 (also 1.719 to E, 1.028 to D—flexibility triad). L31 shows transient suppression from aromatic neurons (N31:3965 projects -1.342 toward F/Y), but L32 recovers with N32:2263 projecting 1.331. These are explicit votes for glycine, not representation character.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L33)
deep_dives.caption: The decisive features: F33:1155 (MLP, 144.6 proj), F33:132 (MLP, 133.7), F33:3601 (MLP, 133.6) are glycine-specific prediction channels that deliver the final 99.58% confidence. These are the model's highest-level decision features, integrating all evidence for structural flexibility constraint.

deep_dives.label: Attention erasers (L28-32)
deep_dives.caption: Key attention heads suppress alternatives: L28H2 projects -2.231 (local eraser, 98.9% local attention), L20H4 projects -1.926 (local eraser), L32H16 projects -1.886 (structural eraser, 10.3% structural attention). These heads actively remove incompatible candidates during the decision phase, clearing the way for glycine.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts glycine with 99.6% confidence by recognizing position 10's structural role as a tight turn requiring exceptional backbone flexibility. Early layers (1-12) build a hydrophobic-leaning representation from local sequence context, but this is overridden at L16 when structural constraint features activate (F16:10 projects 0.617). The decisive evidence is the convergence of flexibility-encoding features: glycine lacks a side chain, making it uniquely suited for conformationally restricted positions. Decision-phase MLP neurons (L28-33) cast overwhelming votes for glycine, with L30 neuron N30:272 projecting 1.231 and final-layer features F33:1155, F33:132, F33:3601 delivering projections of 144.6, 133.7, and 133.6. The model's reasoning is structurally sound: this position demands flexibility, and glycine is the optimal solution.
